{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17415493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17415493"},"attributes":{"position":51,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T09:06:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T09:06:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12900"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518217","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518217"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:01:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:01:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12900"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"12900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12900"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.53,0.37,0.05,0.01,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5338"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41343"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5338"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12900"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26071"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"93"},{"type":"tags","id":"288"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1095"},{"type":"tags","id":"3579"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9574"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12234"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43367"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43899"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44830"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41343"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents with a four-month history of pain in both knee joints, as well as her left hip and shoulder joints. She has been experiencing fever and blurred vision for the past week. She was diagnosed with Crohn\u0027s disease six years ago, and is currently experiencing a flare-up. She also has underlying Type 1 diabetes. Her maternal grandmother and uncle have underlying history of rheumatoid arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe reports engaging in sexual activities with multiple male and female partners and was diagnosed with bacterial vaginosis lately. All other screenings for STIs returned negative results. She denies any recent overseas travel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring the examination, her blood pressure is measured at 126/78 mmHg, pulse at 94/min, and temperature at 37.8\u00b0C. Mild restriction in the range of movements is observed in both knee joints and the left hip joints, accompanied by tenderness and swelling. Additionally, abdominal tenderness is noted upon palpation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Enteropathic arthritis","Reactive arthritis","Rheumatoid arthritis","Viral arthritis","Septic arthritis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnteropathic arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E is a spondyloarthritis (SpA) that occurs in patients with inflammatory bowel diseases (IBDs). Articular changes can be diagnosed before, concurrently with, or after the diagnosis of IBD. In general, arthritis has been estimated to affect 6% to 46% of patients with IBD and may primarily manifest with axial involvement (spondylitis and sacroiliitis), peripheral joint involvement (most common), or both axial and peripheral features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPeripheral arthritis is usually acute and intermittent, displaying asymmetric involvement that often coincides with an IBD relapse. These symptoms frequently resolve within six months. Additionally, it may be linked to other extra-intestinal manifestations, such as uveitis, which can cause blurry vision, as observed in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReactive arthritis \u003C/strong\u003Eis an inflammatory arthritis triggered by bacterial infections in the genitourinary or gastrointestinal tract. Patients typically present with asymmetric oligoarthritis, usually appearing one to four weeks after the initial infection (commonly presents as diarrhoea or urethritis). The most common triggers are intestinal infections (with \u003Cem\u003ESalmonella\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EShigella\u003C/em\u003E or \u003Cem\u003ECampylobacter\u003C/em\u003E) and sexually transmitted infections (with \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E). \u003Cem\u003EGardnerella vaginalis\u003C/em\u003E, responsible for bacterial vaginosis, is not commonly recognised as a cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by complaints of pain and swelling in multiple joints, accompanied by early morning stiffness lasting for \u0026gt;1h. It typically manifests as symmetric polyarthritis with involvement of the wrist and small joints, particularly the metacarpophalangeal or proximal interphalangeal joints. These are not seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E is generally self-limiting and does not require specific intervention. Many viruses, such as Zika, Chikungunya, and SARS-CoV-2, can cause joint pain and inflammation. Common features include a sudden onset of polyarthritis accompanied by flu-like symptoms and systemic signs like a viral rash, fever, and swollen lymph nodes. The absence of such signs and a relevant travel history put viral arthritis as a less likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeptic arthritis \u003C/strong\u003Eshould be considered among the differential diagnoses, especially considering her risk factor of Type 1 diabetes. Patients with IBD are more prone to infections as they are often put on immunosuppressive therapy to control the disease progression. Although the fever points towards a possible infectious cause, septic arthritis usually presents acutely as monoarticular joint involvement, unlike this subacute and polyarticular presentation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Enteropathic arthritis occurs in patients with IBD, and may primarily manifest with axial involvement, peripheral joint involvement, or both axial and peripheral features.","Rheumatic manifestations are the most frequent extraintestinal manifestation in IBD patients."],"references":["Peluso R, Di Minno MN, Iervolino S, Manguso F, Tramontano G, Ambrosino P, et al. Enteropathic spondyloarthritis: from diagnosis to treatment. Clin Dev Immunol [Internet]. 2013 Oct [cited 2023 Sep 7];2013:631408. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3649644/ doi: 10.1155/2013/631408","Shahid Z, Lucke M. Enteropathic Arthritis. In:StatPearls [Internet] 2023 Jul 17. StatPearls Publishing. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK594239/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26071"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12900"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26071"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-10T03:44:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-01-10T03:44:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5338"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41343"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/39"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"dat